// JavaScriptObject — the catch-all class for values that come out of
// JavaScript / TypeScript code without resolvable static types. A
// transpiled `function f(x) { return x + x; }` parameter `x` is
// declared `JavaScriptObject x` because the source had no type
// annotation and the value could be anything.
//
// Today this is intentionally a near-empty class. Sutra's substrate
// already handles vector arithmetic and the auto-promotion of
// scalars to vectors, so for numeric JS code, treating
// JavaScriptObject as "just a vector" is enough — `x + x` lowers to
// tensor addition without further help. Real JS semantics (type
// coercion in `+` between strings and numbers, ===-vs-==, prototype
// chains, etc.) live in deferred work.
//
// Spec: not yet written as a dedicated planning/sutra-spec/ file —
// the surface lives in this stdlib declaration plus the TS
// transpiler's lower.py (which emits JavaScriptObject.wrap(...) at
// primitive-into-JSO-param call sites). Emma 2026-05-10 flagged
// that JSO is the right home for JavaScript-coercion semantics
// (`+` with string concat, ===/== distinction, truthy table,
// typeof, etc.); those overrides will land here as the TS surface
// demands them. CLAUDE.md § "Vibe-coded projects" carves JSO out
// as intentional compatibility code (not legacy-to-remove).
//
// Two static intrinsic methods land 2026-05-08 to make the TS
// transpiler's untyped path actually compile:
//   - `JavaScriptObject.wrap(value)` lifts a primitive (int / float /
//     string / bool) into a JavaScriptObject. Named `wrap` rather
//     than `from` because `from` is a Python keyword and the static-
//     intrinsic dispatch would emit `_VSA.from(...)` — a syntax error.
//     The TS transpiler emits `JavaScriptObject.wrap(7)` for any
//     primitive literal passed to a JavaScriptObject parameter.
//   - `JavaScriptObject.js_add(a, b)` is JavaScript's coercive `+`.
//     The MVP returns element-wise vector add; numeric semantics
//     are correct for number-axis operands. String concatenation
//     under `+` is the next step (would dispatch to `string_concat`
//     when both sides have AXIS_STRING_FLAG set).

class JavaScriptObject extends vector {
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject wrap(vector value);
    // Coercive `+`. When either operand has AXIS_STRING_FLAG set,
    // dispatches to string concatenation; otherwise element-wise
    // vector add (numeric path). Per the 2026-05-10 JSO override pass.
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_add(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    // Strict equality. Per Emma 2026-05-10: the Sutra interpretation
    // of `===` is `defuzzify(a == b)` — the same fuzzy equality `==`
    // gives, with an extra defuzzify step that polarizes the result
    // along the truth axis. More strictness, fuzzy-stripped, NOT
    // JavaScript's reference-equality semantics. For JSO operands
    // this matches "compare with no coercion"; for everything else
    // it's a usable stricter `==`.
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_strict_eq(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    // Strict inequality. `!==` — negation of `===`. Returns a
    // polarized fuzzy on the truth axis (+1 for not-strictly-equal,
    // -1 for strictly equal).
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_strict_neq(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    // Loose equality. `==` with JS coercion: when comparing across
    // primitive kinds (string-vs-number, bool-vs-number), the
    // values are coerced to a common kind before comparing. For
    // same-kind operands this is equivalent to ===. The
    // implementation reads AXIS_STRING_FLAG to detect string
    // operands and applies the coercion ladder.
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_loose_eq(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    // Loose inequality. `!=` — negation of loose `==`.
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_loose_neq(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    // Ordered comparisons (`<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=`) — ECMAScript Abstract
    // Relational Comparison. Both-string operands compare
    // lexicographically by codepoint; otherwise both sides are coerced
    // to numbers and compared numerically on AXIS_REAL. NaN on either
    // side makes all four return false (the JS quirk that prevents
    // defining `<=` as `!(a > b)`; each operator is explicit).
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_lt(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_gt(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_le(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_ge(JavaScriptObject a, JavaScriptObject b);
    // JavaScript truthiness — returns a fuzzy on the truth axis,
    // +1 for truthy values (non-zero numbers, non-empty strings,
    // non-null objects), -1 for falsy values (0, "", null,
    // undefined, NaN, false). Polarized fuzzy, not host bool.
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_truthy(JavaScriptObject a);
    // `typeof a` — returns a String value carrying one of:
    // "number", "string", "boolean", "object", "undefined".
    // Detected by reading the value's flag axes.
    static intrinsic method JavaScriptObject js_typeof(JavaScriptObject a);
}
